# debugging-silent-pipeline-stage-via-argparse-required-grep — History

## v1.1.0 (2026-05-25)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus epic #550 (run_automation_loop.sh silent-abort follow-up). Symptom from v1.0.0 (PR #543) resurfaced; root cause was a DIFFERENT bug — `set -e` abort in backgrounded subshell.

**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed

- Added "Verified Workflow — Cause B: `set -e` abort in backgrounded subshell" as a new section after the existing v1.0.0 Verified Workflow (which is now implicitly Cause A).
- Added 2 new Failed Attempts rows: "assume prior fix is the only cause" and "trust set -e inside backgrounded function".
- Extended description and "When to Use" to mention the second cause.
- Added new tags: set-e, errexit, backgrounded, subshell, process-repo, second-cause.

### Why

v1.0.0 shipped on 2026-05-24 documenting the argparse-required-flag missing-pass cause (PR #543). On 2026-05-25 the symptom returned: the same orchestrator (`scripts/run_automation_loop.sh`) appeared to "skip through repos because plans already exist" — phases 2-6 silent, only phase 1 visible. Initial hypothesis was the v1.0.0 cause had regressed. The v1.0.0 grep methodology cleared (all phase CLIs received their required flags correctly; no `|| echo` swallow at the phase call site was suppressing argparse exit 2). The second cause was: `process_repo` ran under inherited `set -euo pipefail` and an unguarded infrastructure command (most likely `git fetch origin --quiet` or `mapfile` under `set -m`) aborted the function silently between phase 1 (planner exit 0) and phase 2 (review-plans). Fix: `set +e` + `trap 'set -e' RETURN` inside the function, plus per-phase START/done banners for observability.

The lesson — when a silent-stage symptom resurfaces, do NOT assume the prior fix is sufficient — is the principal v1.1.0 amendment. The cross-reference to [[audit-driven-remediation-workflow]] is also added (that skill is being amended in parallel to capture the downstream-consumer-drift pattern from the same session).

